Overpass

Target IP: 10.10.186.247

What happens when some broke CompSci students make a password manager?

Scanning


There are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP


The webpage above is displayed for this web application. This website is about a password manager application created by a team of young developers.


The aboutus page contains the possible usernames.


Doing a directory search against shows the interesting entries above.


The login.js JavaScript source-code contains the code above. It looks like if the cookies are set then the /admin page is shown. Inside the JavaScript console, I entered the code Cookies.set("SessionToken", "") to set the session.


And now I have access to the /admin page which contains a SSH key. There is also the username james and paradox.


I copied the SSH key to my machine and used ssh2john to obtain the passphrase james13. Now I should be able to login the target machine using this SSH key as james.

Exploitation


After changing the permission of the SSH key to 400, I gained access to the target machine using this key by SSH. Now I have a foothold on the target machine.

Privilege Escalation


The todo.txt file contains the content above. Hmm... what if the user has saved passwords on the machine?


Using the command find / -name "*overpass*" -type f 2>/dev/null, I found the location of the overpass application at /usr/bin. Then using this, I obtained all the saved passwords on the machine. The password saydrawnlyingpicture is interesting.


There is an interesting cronjob that gets executed by root. It makes a curl request and executes the buildscript.sh script using bash.


On my machine, I set up the buildcript.sh file that contains the reverse shell script shown on top terminal in the picture above. This script opens a reverse shell connection on port 8443.


On the target machine, I edited the /etc/hosts file and added 10.14.55.153 overpass.thm to point to my target machine. This will call the buildscript.sh on my target machine for the reverse shell.


After a few seconds, I gained a reverse shell connection. Now I have root access on the target machine.

Flags


The user.txt flag once I gained a foothold on the target machine as james using the SSH key.
